**W1-D4-Class_Methods_Employee**

**What are you learning today?**
Until now every attribute (`self.name`, `self.balance`) belonged to one specific object. Today you learn class variables — data shared across ALL objects, not separate per object. Also learning two new method types: `@classmethod` and a new way to create objects from different input formats.

---

**1. Employee**

```python
class Employee:
    total_employees = 0      
    # class variable — lives on the CLASS itself, not on any one object
    # shared by every Employee object ever created
    # think of it like a shared counter on the wall everyone can see

    company_name = "TechCorp"  
    # another class variable — same value for every employee
    # accessible without creating any object: Employee.company_name

    def __init__(self, name, salary):
        self.name = name        # instance variable — belongs to this specific object only
        self.salary = salary    # instance variable — separate per object
        Employee.total_employees += 1  
        # every time a new Employee is created, increase the shared counter by 1
        # notice: Employee.total_employees not self.total_employees
        # using self.total_employees would create a separate copy on each object — wrong

    @classmethod
    def get_total_employees(cls):  
        # @classmethod decorator — this method works on the CLASS, not one object
        # cls = the class itself (Employee), not self (one object)
        return cls.total_employees  
        # reads the shared counter from the class

    @classmethod
    def from_string(cls, data_string):  
        # alternate constructor — creates an Employee from a string like "Ravi-30000"
        # useful when data comes in different formats (from a file, API response etc)
        name, salary = data_string.split("-")  
        # split("-") breaks "Ravi-30000" into ["Ravi", "30000"]
        # name = "Ravi", salary = "30000" (still a string)
        return cls(name, int(salary))  
        # int(salary) converts "30000" string to 30000 number
        # cls(name, int(salary)) = Employee(name, int(salary)) — creates and returns new object

e1 = Employee("Ravi", 30000)
e2 = Employee("Sai", 40000)
e3 = Employee.from_string("Kiran-28000")  
# created using classmethod instead of normal way
# useful when input comes as a string, not separate values

print(Employee.get_total_employees())  # 3 — counts all objects created
print(Employee.company_name)           # TechCorp — no object needed
print(e3.name, e3.salary)              # Kiran 28000
```

