**Class variable vs Instance variable**

```python
# WRONG — using self instead of Employee for shared counter
def __init__(self, name, salary):
    self.name = name
    self.salary = salary
    self.total_employees += 1  
    # this creates a SEPARATE total_employees on each object
    # e1.total_employees = 1
    # e2.total_employees = 1
    # e3.total_employees = 1
    # Employee.total_employees stays 0 — shared counter never updated
    # no crash, just silently wrong — most dangerous kind of bug
```

---

**Key things to remember:**
- Class variable = shared by ALL objects, defined at top of class without `self`
- Instance variable = belongs to one specific object, defined with `self.x = x` inside `__init__`
- `@classmethod` takes `cls` (the class) instead of `self` (one object)
- Use `Employee.total_employees` not `self.total_employees` when updating shared data
- `from_string` pattern is common in real backend code — data comes from APIs/files in different formats, you need flexible ways to create objects
- Django managers (`Post.objects.create()`, `Post.objects.filter()`) work similarly to classmethods — called on the class, not one object

